<span id="fn_438"></span>[439](cc10017.htm#fr_438.md) <span
id="xviii.ii-p7.2"></span>

<span id="xviii.ii-p8"></span> Gebal, which signifies a mountain,
denotes, according to some, the Giblites, who inhabited a district on
the Phoenician coast in the neighborhood of Tyre. They were a tribe of
the Aborigines of Canaan, and are mentioned as left by Joshua to be
conquered after his death, (<span id="xviii.ii-p8.1"></span>[Jos
13:5](../../../bib/kjv/jos013.htm#005)<span id="xviii.ii-p8.1"></span>..md)
They were of considerable service to Hiram, king of Tyre, in preparing
materials for Solomon’s temple, as we learn from <span
id="xviii.ii-p8.2"></span>[1Ki
5:18](../../../bib/kjv/kg1005.htm#018.md)<span id="xviii.ii-p8.2"></span>,
where the original word for *stone-squarers* is <span
id="xviii.ii-p8.3"></span>הגבלים *haggibelim*, *the Giblites*; and it
would seem from Ezekiel’s speaking of “the ancients of Gebal and the
wise men thereof,” (<span id="xviii.ii-p8.4"></span>[Eze
27:9](../../../bib/kjv/eze027.htm#009)<span id="xviii.ii-p8.4"></span>,.md)
that they rose to no small degree of eminence. The ruins of an ancient
city called by the natives Gibyle, situated upon the Mediterranean Sea
between Tripoli and Sidon, are supposed to be those of the chief city of
the Giblites. If so, these ruins attest its ancient grandeur to have
been considerable. Others suppose that Gebal (the Gebalene of the
Romans) was a mountainous district inhabited by the Edomites, and
extending from the Dead Sea southward to Selal or Petra. By the Arabs it
is called Djebal.

